$interpreted: Baa Baa: That fur the boss wanted has arrived. You can take it to him. Ah, and the teahouse is nearly out of tea leaves, so remember to get some more in.
Kai-Tai Employee: Understood! We'll be right there.
Baa Baa: Oh, and also, on Hot Spring Street...
Yang-Tai: I knew you'd take to this like a duck to water. It's been barely a week and you're running the place almost single-handedly.
Baa Baa: I'm just doing like ya taught me. It's all thanks to you for giving me a chance in the first place.
Papa Gu: Looks like business is good today, too.
Baa Baa: G'dday, Papa Gu—I'm sorry, I haven't had time to welcome you. Are you here to see today's accounts?
Papa Gu: Don't you worry about welcoming me. Just keep making your pa proud.
Baa Baa: Stop kiddin' around! How many times have I told ya, I'm just here to do a few odd jobs—I'm not qualified to be the President's daughter!
Papa Gu: Sigh~ President Yang, little Baa Baa here's so lovely and dependable. You're lucky to have such a good little girl—You've nothing to be complaining about!
Yang-Tai: Hey, cut it out. You know I don't have any kids. Besides, I'm happy enough just to have her around me.
Baa Baa: Don't be silly, President.
Papa Gu: Heheh. President Yang's always had a good reputation for treating people with honesty. He's famous for it in all our circles.
Papa Gu: If he says something, he means it. You'd better start calling him Pops, little Baa Baa~
Baa Baa: C'mon, knock it off you two...
Baa Baa: Oh, by the way, President, I saw something odd when I was doing the inventory just now.
Baa Baa: I dunno why we've got so many home goods still in stock, I remember they sold out like hotcakes already.
Yang-Tai: Oh~ I set aside some reserves, they could come in handy later.
Baa Baa: Got it~ Keep a few back, and then we can hike up the prices.
Yang-Tai: No, no, no. I meant we can sell them at half price to those who might need them.
Baa Baa: Surely you've got it all backwards, President? Won't they go up in value if we hold them back?
Yang-Tai: There'll always be times of need ahead.
Baa Baa: But doing business is about making money, and people'll hand over even more dosh for something they need.
Papa Gu: Don't argue with him, Baa Baa, unless you want a good scolding.
Yang-Tai: I wouldn't scold anyone over such a thing. Baa Baa's been scrapping for herself for too long, but she'll soon understand.
Papa Gu: Okay, okay. Anyhow, I came to talk to you about that thing.
Yang-Tai: Oh? How's it looking?
Papa Gu: Not good. I suggest you keep out of it.
Yang-Tai: Everyone has to make a living somehow. We can't just ignore this. And it'll be a good opportunity, too—Baa Baa, come with me.
Baa Baa: Where are we going, President?
Yang-Tai: Don't worry, you'll see.
Honey Badger Thug: Where's my money, kid! This is your final day!
Demihuman Merchant: I-I-I'm sorry... Business has been so bad lately, please won't you forget the interest again this month?
Honey Badger Thug: Forget the interest, he says! You seemed pretty sure of yourself when you came to me in the first place. Sure, we can forget the interest. I'll just take your shop as collateral.
Demihuman Merchant: No, please! I can't get by without my shop.
Honey Badger Thug: That ain't my problem!
Yang-Tai: Wait! I can pay his debt for him.
Yang-Tai: Making a scene like this won't do anyone any good.
Honey Badger Thug: You again... Humph! Fine.
Demihuman Merchant: Thank you, President Yang, I'm ever so grateful.
Yang-Tai: Don't mention it. Here~
Demihuman Merchant: Oh, I can't, I can't accept anything more from you!
Yang-Tai: Nobody has it easy. That's why we've got to all look out for each other. This'll at least help you get through a spot of hardship.
Demihuman Merchant: I'll never forget how kind you've been.
Yang-Tai: I best be going, I've plenty more people to see.
Baa Baa: I just don't get it, President. What's in it for you?
Baa Baa: That shop of his was proper old 'n' munted, he won't be seeing a turn for the better any time soon, ya know?
Yang-Tai: Every business has its ups and downs.
Baa Baa: He'd best close up for good, if you ask me.
Baa Baa: S'pose we help him and it comes back to bite us on the tush? We wouldn't be able to get our cash back, and then we'd be left strapped, too.
Baa Baa: Instead of giving out freebies, we could buy him out. That'd be much more profitable~
Yang-Tai: Baa Baa... We're in business to make money, it's true. But we should still be doing it the right and decent way.
Yang-Tai: To put it bluntly, we do this so we can help each other out.
Baa Baa: The decent way... helping each other...
Yang-Tai: We demihumans don't have an easy time of it here in the East. I started the Kai-Tai Group hoping we could all have a better life.
Baa Baa: So yer saying... You wouldn't have helped me if I weren't a demihuman?
Yang-Tai: Of course not. We should do what we can to help anybody in need, no matter who they are. That's the Kai-Tai Group's mission~
Baa Baa: I see... Doesn't sound so juicy to me...
Yang-Tai: Some day you'll understand the true value of things.
Person Receiving Aid: I can't thank you enough.

Baa Baa: All they have to do is say thank you and they get a handful of dosh. Sounds like a good deal to me. If that's all there is to it, I'll just have to say a bajillion thank yous, and I'll be sorted.
